Runs a scripted keystroke stream (`Event::Mark`/`Text`/`Key`) through the `Sim` editor model and packages the outcome into an `EditorState` for test/comparison purposes.

The one non-obvious behavior: `target` in the returned `EditorState` is always the landing position recorded for mark `0` specifically (`landing.get(&0)`), not the last mark seen or any other index — other marks recorded via `Event::Mark(n)` for `n != 0` are collected into `landing` but silently discarded in the result. `Event::Key { key, n }` replays `apply_key` `n` times rather than passing a repeat count into `Sim`, so any repeat-aware key handling must live in `Sim::apply_key` itself. `Event::Mark` records the cursor position *before* any further events are applied, at the moment the mark event is processed in stream order.

`interpret(events: &[Event], b: Behaviors) -> EditorState` is the sole public entry point; it constructs a fresh `Sim` per call (no reuse across invocations). Depends on `Sim`, `Behaviors`, `EditorState`, and `Event` from sibling modules (`sim.rs` and the parent `editor` module) — the `Event` enum's variant shapes (`Mark(u32)`, `Text(String)`, `Key{key, n}`) must stay in sync with whatever constructs the event stream (likely a parser/generator elsewhere in `editor`).